  "text": "Among the few genes known to be involved in negative selection of thymocytes are the orphan steroid receptor nur77 and the pro-apoptotic Bcl-2 family member bim (9,10). Both genes are identi®ed by our microarray analysis, validating the use of this approach. Negative selection is impaired in transgenic mice expressing a dominant-negative mutant form of nur77 (9). While Bim induces mitochondrial dysfunction (5), the molecular mechanism of nur77-mediated apoptosis is unclear. Although fasL and cd30 have been proposed as target genes, nur77-mediated apoptosis is not impaired by the absence of these genes [CITATION_1] . A recent report suggests a transcription-independent apoptotic function of nur77 directly targeting the mitochondria [CITATION_2] . Yet, nur77-mediated apoptosis in T cells is not impaired by Bcl-2 overexpression (9) and transcriptional activity of Nur77 correlates with apoptosis in thymocytes (64) making this possibility in thymocytes less likely.",
